title: NASA and Boeing say preparations continue for July Starliner test flight
summary: NASA and Boeing said May 26 they are still working towards a July launch of the CST-100 Starliner on a crewed test flight despite “emerging issues” and concerns raised by a safety panel.

title: SpaceX launches Badr-8 to bolster Arabsat’s satellite fleet
summary: SpaceX launched the Badr-8 TV broadcast and telecoms satellite May 27 for Saudi Arabia-based fleet operator Arabsat, equipped with a jamming-resistant optical communications payload demonstrator.

title: NASA Sets Coverage for Axiom Mission 2 Departure from Space Station
summary: NASA will provide live coverage of the undocking and departure of Axiom Mission 2 (Ax-2) private astronaut mission from the International Space Station before crew returns to Earth.

title: Space Development Agency to launch 13 satellites in late June
summary: The Space Development Agency is preparing to launch at least 13 satellites in late June, the agency’s director Derek Tournear said May 26.

title: Falcon 9 launches Arabsat 7B following weather delays
summary: SpaceX finally launched the Arabsat 7B satellite to geostationary transfer orbit (GTO) for Arabsat atop its Falcon 9 rocket.

title: Rocket Lab’s Electron delivers TROPICS constellation to orbit
summary: Electron, Rocket Lab’s small satellite launch vehicle, launched twice, just ~2 weeks apart from the companies Launch Complex 1 in Mahia, New...

title: NASA Pursues Lunar Terrain Vehicle Services for Artemis Missions
summary: NASA is seeking industry proposals for a next-generation LTV (Lunar Terrain Vehicle) that will allow astronauts to go farther and conduct more science than ever before as they explore the south polar region of the Moon during Artemis missions.

title: DARPA seeks AI tools to automate tracking of satellite sensor data
summary: BAE Systems won a $7 million contract from the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency to develop AI tools to automate the tracking of data collected by military satellites.

title: Software problem blamed for ispace lunar lander crash
summary: A software glitch kept a lunar lander from properly determining its altitude, leading to a crash on its landing attempt last month, Japanese company ispace announced May 26.

title: L3Harris wins $80 million Air Force contract for satcom experiments
summary: The U.S. Air Force Research Laboratory awarded L3Harris Technologies a contract worth $80.8 million to conduct communications experiments using multiple commercial space internet services.
